onialism, and representations of humanness. Sylvia Wynter: On Being Human as Praxis is a critical genealogy of Wynter's work, highlighting her insights on how race, location, and time together inform what it means to be human. The contributors explore Wynter's stunning reconceptualization of the human in relation to concepts of blackness, modernity, urban space, the Caribbean, science studies, migratory politics, and the interconnectedness of creative and theoretical resistances. The collection includes an extensive conversation between Sylvia Wynter and Katherine McKittrick that delineates Wynter's engagement with writers such as Frantz Fanon, W. E. B. DuBois, and Aimé Césaire, among others; the interview also reveals the ever-extending range and power of Wynter's intellectual project, and elucidates her attempts to rehistoricize humanness as praxis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChoreographerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aCivilization, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aDancerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 0aLiterature and societyxJamaica. 0aPostcolonialism. 0aRacexPhilosophy. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnsfield, Bench, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyce Davies, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEudell, Demetrius L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira da Silva, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKittrick, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKittrick, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSharma, Nandita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct